Ille ego, qui qnondam gracili modulatus avena Carmen, et egressus silvis. vicina co’egi Ut quamvis avido parerent arva colono, Gratum opus agricolis .· at nunc horrentia Martis.

THE above verses are usually placed, in the editions of virgil, at the begin· ning of the Aeneid, but printed in a form different from that of the text, as an indication that there is a question as to their authenticity, and as to their proper connection with the poem. They were known to ServiuS, the great commentator on virgil, and seem not unworthy of the poet. But, on the other hand, the lines are not found in the best manuscripts, while “ ali· antiqnity,'' as Ribbeck says, “ recognizes the words arma virumque as the beginning of the poem.’' They were thus understood by Propertius and quoted by Ovid‚ contemporaries practically of the poet, and by the later writers, Martial and Persius. It is possible that these four lines were prefixed by the poet to one or more copies of the first book presented to personal friends. At any rate, although they may be Virgilian, they should not form part of the text.
